    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(11) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "In the porch that is called Solomon’s.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The porch—or better, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "portico",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cloister",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—was outside the Temple, on the eastern side. It consisted, in the Herodian Temple, of a double row of Corinthian columns, about thirty-seven feet high, and received its name as having been in part constructed, when the Temple was rebuilt by Zerubbabel, with the fragments of the older edifice. The people tried to persuade Herod Agrippa the First to pull it down and rebuild it, but he shrank from the risk and cost of such an undertaking (Jos. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ant.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " xx. 9, § 7). It was, like the porticos in all Greek cities, a favourite place of resort, especially as facing the morning sun in winter. (See Note on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 10:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) The memory of what had then been the result of their Master’s teaching must have been fresh in the minds of the two disciples. Then the people had complained of being kept in suspense as to whether Jesus claimed to be the Christ, and, when He spoke of being One with the Father, had taken up stones to stone Him (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 10:31-33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Now they were to hear His name as Holy and Just, as “the Servant of Jehovah,” as the very Christ (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 3:13-14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
