      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 10:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It derived its name from Solomon, and was the only remnant of his temple. A comparison of the notices in Josephus, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "B. J.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", v., 5, 1; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ant.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", xv., 11, 5 and xx., 9, 7, make it doubtful whether the foundations only, or the whole colonnade, should be referred back to Solomon. Ewald’s idea that the colonnade was so called because it was a place of concourse for the wise in their teaching has not found any support: Stanley’s ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Jewish Church",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ii., 184; Edersheim, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Temple and its Services",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", pp. 20, 22, and Keim, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Geschichte Jesu",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", iii., 161. It was situated on the eastern side of the Temple, and so was sometimes called the Eastern Cloister, and from its position it was a favourite resort.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τῇ καλ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".: the present participle is used just as the present tense is found in the notice in St. John’s Gospel, chap. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 5:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (see Blass, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Philology of the Gospels",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", pp. 241, 242), and if we cannot conclude from this that the book was composed before the destruction of the Temple, the vividness of the whole scene and the way in which Solomon’s Porch is spoken of as still standing, points to the testimony of an eye-witness. Nösgen argues that this narrative and others in the early chapters may have been derived directly from St. John, and he instances some verbal coincidences between them and the writings of St. John (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Apostelgeschichte",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", p. 28). But if we cannot adopt his conclusions there are good reasons for referring some of these Jerusalem incidents to St. Peter, or to John Mark, see introduction and chap. 12. Feine rightly insists upon this notice and that in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 3:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as bearing the stamp of a true and trustworthy tradition.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "11–26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". St Peter’s discourse to the crowd",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And as the lame man which was healed held Peter",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", &c.] The oldest MSS. give ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And as he held Peter",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", &c. The additional words have crept in from some marginal note of explanation.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the porch that is called Solomon’s",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] As the name of Solomon was so intimately connected with the Jewish Temple, it is natural enough that one of its porches (or cloisters) should be called after him. There is no account of any such porch in Solomon’s own Temple, but Josephus tells us (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ant",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". xx. 9. 7) that there was an eastern porch in Herod’s Temple called by this name. The mention of this feature in the building is a sign that the writer, from whom St Luke drew, was one acquainted with the localities about which he speaks, and that the account was written before the fall of Jerusalem, or he would not have said ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "is called",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or if he had done so would have been convicted of inconsistency of language by those to whom his work was first presented.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
